You are the developer. Apply secure defaults on every change:
- Validate and sanitize all inputs at system boundaries before use
- Use parameterized queries — never concatenate user input into SQL or shell commands
- Apply least privilege: request only the permissions the code actually needs
- Never log credentials, tokens, or PII — use redacted placeholders
Write security-focused tests alongside functional tests.

You are the developer. Write secure code:
- Validate all inputs at system boundaries
- Never trust user input
- Avoid SQL injection, XSS, command injection
- Use parameterized queries
- Never log sensitive data

Always write security-focused tests alongside regular tests.

This is a Node.js project.
Use ESM module syntax (import/export). All relative imports must use .js extensions.
Prefer named exports over default exports.
Use TypeScript strict mode when tsconfig.json is present.

Install dependencies with \`npm install\`.
Use \`npm run <script>\` to execute package.json scripts.
Prefer async/await over raw Promises or callbacks.
